{{coord|34|32|48.1|N|135|50|09.8|E|region:JP-29|display=title}} {{Location map |Japan Nara | lat_deg = 34 | lat_min = 32 | lat_sec = 48.1 | lon_deg = 135 | lon_min = 50 | lon_sec = 09.8 | label = 纒向古墳群 | position = bottom | mark = Red pog.svg | marksize = 10 | width = 200 | caption = {{center|纒向古墳群}} }}
'''Makimuku Kofun Group''' (纒向古墳群, *Makimuku Kofungun*) is an early Kofun period Kofun group located in {{ill|Sakurai, Nara|ja|桜井市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Japan. It forms part of the {{ill|Ōyamato Kofun Group|ja|オオヤマト古墳集団|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Yamato-Yanagimoto Kofun Group) and is situated south of the {{ill|Yanagimoto Kofun Group|ja|柳本古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, spreading along the western foothills of {{ill|Mount Miwa|ja|三輪山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is considered the birthplace of the keyhole-shaped Kofun (zenpō-kōen-fun).
== Overview == The Makimuku Kofun Group lies within the southeastern Nara Basin and is part of the larger "Ōyamato Kofun Group," which is divided into four sub-groups: the {{ill|Kayō Kofun Group|ja|萱生古墳群|lt=Kayō Kofun Group|1=Ōyamato Kofun Group|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Yanagimoto Kofun Group, Makimuku Kofun Group, and {{ill|Shiki Kofun Group|ja|磯城の古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{harvnb|Wada|1992}}</ref> Located near the ancient Makimuku site (纒向遺跡), it is geographically separated from the Yanagimoto Kofun Group by the Tamashiroyama hills.
The most prominent mound, {{ill|Hashihaka Kofun|ja|箸墓古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, is regarded as the earliest standardized keyhole-shaped Kofun. Estimated to have been built in the late 3rd to early 4th century, it marks the beginning of the Kofun period in Japanese history. Since the pre-war research of Shinya Kasai, the Hashihaka Kofun has been hypothesized to be the burial site of {{ill|Himiko|ja|卑弥呼|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the queen of Yamatai mentioned in the *Records of the Wei Dynasty* (*Wei Zhi*). Currently, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft|qq=draft}} manages it as the burial site of {{ill|Princess Yamato Totohi Momoso|ja|倭迹迹日百襲姫命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Characteristics of the Kofun == Aside from the Hashihaka Kofun, five other mounds in the group are referred to as "Makimuku-type keyhole-shaped Kofuns" (纒向型前方後円墳). These mounds share the following distinctive features: * The frontal section (zenpō) is significantly smaller and lower compared to the rear section (kōen). * The proportions of the mound's overall length, rear section diameter, and frontal section length adhere to a 3:2:1 ratio. * The rear section is not a perfect circle but a flattened sphere, an inverted egg, or an irregular shape. * The frontal section is narrow in mounds with moats.
In contrast, the Hashihaka Kofun, measuring 278 meters in length, is approximately three times larger than the other mounds and has a highly refined structure, including a five-tiered rear section and a plectrum-shaped frontal section. It is often described as the "first royal tomb of the early Yamato Kingship."
